What I audited

I reviewed the English homepage, Chinese homepage, blog index, a blog article, the projects hub, a whole-house project page, and multiple city/service pages. I also noted redirect behavior and how the root domain responded to crawling.

Executive summary for the SEO team

The biggest SEO issues are:

Programmatic pages are indexable, but many appear too templated and too similar.

There are visible content-quality bugs on project pages.

The Chinese version has major localization / trust / international SEO problems.

Service-area pages are locally targeted, but much of the content is generic or semi-generic.

Information consistency is weak across templates, which can hurt E-E-A-T and conversion.

Crawl/indexation behavior should be validated because the root domain returned a bot-verification screen in this audit.

High-priority findings
1) Programmatic SEO footprint is obvious, and some pages are too thin to justify separate indexation

The service-area pages follow a clear template: city breadcrumb, city H1, generic service explanation, localized paragraph, FAQ block, “other areas,” “other services,” and CTA/footer. You can see that pattern on pages like “Kitchen Renovation in Richmond,” “Bathroom Renovation in North Vancouver,” “Whole House Renovation in North Vancouver,” and “Kitchen Renovation in Port Coquitlam.”

That is not automatically bad. The problem is that many of these pages look only lightly differentiated:

the service intro is generic,

the FAQ blocks are repeated,

the CTAs and footer blocks are identical,

local uniqueness is often one or two paragraphs,

some pages use region-mismatched FAQ wording.

A strong example is the Richmond kitchen page: it targets Richmond, but one of its FAQs asks, “What is the average cost of a kitchen renovation in Vancouver?” and another answer says Reno Stars ensures the renovation meets “Vancouver building codes,” even though the page is specifically for Richmond.

Likewise, the Port Coquitlam kitchen page repeats the same Vancouver-oriented FAQ framing, including “average cost of a kitchen renovation in Vancouver” and “Vancouver building codes.”

Why this matters: these pages may be crawlable and keyword-relevant, but Google can still treat them as low-value doorway-like variations if city-level differentiation is too shallow.

Recommendation:

Keep only city/service pages that have enough unique value to deserve indexing.

Add substantial local uniqueness per city:

neighborhood-specific considerations,

permit/inspection notes by municipality,

housing stock differences,

local before/after case studies,

city-specific pricing bands,

city-specific testimonials,

city-specific FAQs,

map/service-area proof and nearby projects.

For thinner combinations, consider consolidating or noindexing until upgraded.

2) There are visible templating/content bugs on project pages, and this is a major quality signal problem

On the “Vancouver Whole House Renovation” page, one included area is rendered as:

“Bathroom Bathroom Renovation Renovation”

followed by “Bathroom Renovation renovation project.”

That is not a minor typo. It strongly suggests a broken content model or template binding. On project/gallery pages, these issues can damage:

index quality,

user trust,

snippet quality,

and Google’s assessment of overall site quality.

There are similar signs elsewhere:

homepage project list contains awkward or duplicated labels like “Bathroom Bathroom Renovation Renovation.”

some search-result snippets also expose repetitive project-title structures and compressed formatting, which makes the site feel auto-generated rather than editorially controlled.

Recommendation:

Treat this as a release-blocker for SEO.

Run a full crawl to catch:

duplicated taxonomy names,

malformed project titles,

missing/empty fields,

repeated service scope strings,

broken alt text,

placeholder labels,

duplicated “before” assets or captions.

Add schema/content validation in the CMS or build pipeline so bad field merges cannot publish.

3) Multilingual SEO is currently a serious weakness, especially on the Chinese version

The Chinese homepage has multiple problems at once:

a) English title/meta-style messaging on a Chinese URL

The Chinese page is presented with an English title in the audit and includes English promotional copy within the body, such as:
“Experienced Home Remodeling Contractors in Vancouver...” while the surrounding page is Chinese.

b) Mixed-language body content

The Chinese page contains English reviews and English UI fragments mixed with Chinese content.

c) Machine-translation / broken-Chinese quality

Parts of the Chinese copy read like low-quality machine translation, for example:
“在Reno的星星，我们提供全面的温哥华的翻修方案经理的每一个细节...” and “你的空间应该得到什么，但最好的。”

d) Inconsistent business facts between languages

The English homepage says:

“over 30 years of experience,”

“700+ projects completed,”

“a team of 100+ professionals,”

“$5M liability coverage,”

“3-year warranty.”

But the Chinese page shows different numbers in the visible content:

“超过 27 年的综合经验”

“17 名技术娴熟的团队成员”

This is a trust issue, not just a translation issue.

e) Translation plugin footprint is visible

The blog article and Chinese page visibly reference TranslatePress / language-switch artifacts.

Why this matters: if both languages are indexable, poor localization can hurt brand trust, conversion, and international relevance signals. In some cases, it can also create duplicate/near-duplicate content problems or weak language targeting.

Recommendation:

Do a full bilingual QA pass before expanding Chinese indexation.

Decide whether Chinese pages should be:

fully localized and indexed, or

partially deindexed until professionally rewritten.

Align all company facts across languages from one source of truth.

Verify hreflang, canonicals, sitemap language pairs, and indexation rules.

Remove machine-translated pages from index until they are human-edited.

4) The blog exists, but its architecture is weak for non-brand organic growth

The blog index has only 7 articles, all shown as published on Mar 12, 2026, and nearly all of them are case-study style posts.

The blog article sample also shows a slug/title mismatch:

URL slug says “kitchen-renovation-costs-in-vancouver-2024-guide”

H1 says “Kitchen Renovation Costs in Vancouver (2025 Guide)”

That creates freshness ambiguity and weakens editorial trust.

The blog currently appears to skew toward project storytelling rather than full-funnel search intent. The case studies are useful, but they do not replace high-intent articles like:

kitchen renovation cost Vancouver,

bathroom renovation cost Vancouver,

permit requirements by city,

condo renovation strata rules,

timeline by renovation type,

ROI guides,

kitchen cabinet refacing vs replacement,

basement legal-suite renovation considerations.

Recommendation:
Split blog/content into at least three clusters:

Commercial intent: cost, quote, service comparisons, timelines.

Local intent: city-specific permit/strata/planning guides.

Trust intent: case studies, process explainers, materials, workmanship, warranty.

Also fix:

publish-date integrity,

slug/title year consistency,

author/reviewer/editor fields if possible,

internal links from articles to service/city/project pages.

5) Homepage positioning is strong for users, but broad for SEO

The homepage is clearly optimized around “Vancouver Home Renovation Experts” with service categories, trust signals, reviews, showroom, and service areas.

That is good for conversion, but the homepage is also trying to do a lot:

broad company positioning,

all services,

all cities,

all social proof,

all FAQs,

all contact paths,

project portfolio,

blog teasers.

The result is that the homepage is strong as a brand page, but it should not carry the ranking burden for every service + city keyword.

Recommendation:
Use the homepage for brand + primary market positioning only:

“Vancouver renovation contractor”

“kitchen, bathroom, full-home renovation”

“Lower Mainland”

strong proof and CTA

Then let dedicated pages rank for:

service intent,

city-service intent,

cost intent,

case-study intent,

design inspiration intent.

6) Internal linking is present, but still looks template-driven instead of topic-driven

There is internal linking between services, projects, blog, other areas, and other services. That is a positive baseline.

But a lot of it is structural rather than strategic:

footer-wide links,

“other areas,”

“other services,”

“view all projects.”

What is still missing is stronger contextual internal linking:

from city/service pages to matching case studies in that city,

from cost guides to exact service pages,

from project pages to the relevant city/service landing page,

from service pages to process, FAQ, warranty, materials, and blog resources.

Recommendation:
Create internal-link blocks based on intent:

“Related projects in Richmond”

“Cost guide for this service”

“Permit notes for this city”

“Our process for this renovation type”

“Similar kitchen renovations in Vancouver”

That builds topical depth better than just sitewide navigation.

7) E-E-A-T and trust signals are good, but consistency issues are undermining them

The site has many strong trust elements:

30+ years experience,

700+ projects,

warranty,

$5M liability coverage,

WCB mention,

client reviews,

showroom address,

service-area coverage,

partner brands.

Those are useful.

But the trust package becomes weaker when:

multilingual claims do not match,

templating bugs are visible,

year labels are inconsistent,

translation quality is poor,

some pages look mass-generated.

Recommendation:
Centralize all trust facts into one structured content source:

years experience,

number of projects,

warranty terms,

team size,

insurance,

certifications,

showroom address,

review-platform references.

Then render them everywhere from the same data source.

8) Crawl/indexation needs technical validation because the root domain behavior is unusual

When I opened the bare root domain, it returned a “Verifying that you are not a robot...” screen. But the language subdirectory /en/ was accessible and rendered normally.

This does not prove Googlebot is blocked, but it is enough to justify technical validation. If WAF/bot protection behaves inconsistently by path, user-agent, or region, it can affect crawling, rendering, or canonical discovery.

I also observed URL normalization/redirect behavior:

/en/ resolved to https://www.reno-stars.com/en/

the blog URL path /en/vancouver-renovation-blog/ redirected to /en/blog/

Redirects themselves are fine, but they should be checked at scale.

Recommendation for technical team:

test with Google Search Console URL Inspection,

verify Googlebot is not challenged by the WAF,

validate canonicals on all indexable templates,

validate hreflang tags,

verify XML sitemaps include only canonical, indexable URLs,

check for mixed www/non-www references,

check that language versions self-canonicalize correctly,

confirm robots/meta robots by template.

I could not directly confirm robots.txt, sitemap XML contents, or page-source canonicals in this pass, so that part should be confirmed with a crawler or direct server-side inspection.

Medium-priority findings
9) Some city pages are stronger than others, but many still need more unique local substance

A few city pages do include useful local references:

Richmond mentions code/inspection familiarity,

Vancouver cabinet refacing mentions strata and heritage homes,

North Vancouver mentions coastal/rainy climate and neighborhoods.

That is a good direction.

But to compete locally, each city page should add more evidence that Reno Stars truly operates there:

2–4 project cards from that city,

city-specific testimonial,

municipality-specific FAQ,

local permit/process content,

embedded service-area map or radius,

local material/structural constraints,

city-specific before/after gallery.

Without that, pages can still look generated for coverage rather than built from real local experience.

10) Project pages have useful structured content, but not enough narrative uniqueness

The project pages do include fields such as:

location,

timeline,

space type,

budget,

included areas,

challenge,

solution,

service scope.

That is a good content model. The issue is that the prose is often brief and formulaic.

Recommendation:
For every project, expand with:

homeowner goals,

starting condition,

constraints,

materials selected and why,

scope changes,

approvals/permits/strata notes,

craftsmanship details,

outcome metrics,

related service/city links.

This helps both SEO and conversion.

11) Brand/search snippet hygiene needs cleanup

The blog article slug/H1 year mismatch is one example of snippet hygiene problems.

Other possible snippet concerns visible in crawled text:

title/body mismatches across languages,

repetitive phrasing,

odd compressed text in project snippets,

some pages leading with generic lines like “Professional renovation services in Richmond” or “Renovations in North Vancouver.”

Those are serviceable, but not strong CTR copy.

Recommendation:
Rewrite titles/meta descriptions and intro copy by template:

service pages: include city + service + differentiator,

project pages: include city + style/scope + outcome,

articles: include year only when maintained annually,

Chinese pages: native-language snippet copy only.